				</div>
			
				<div class="comment-text">
					
					<p>Hi Patrice, I&#8217;ve heard of this happening to the old Furbies but this is the first I&#8217;ve heard for the new ones.  The old models would sometimes freeze up (aka the motor would lock up).  This required taking the skin off and disassembling the Furby, turning the motor with a screw driver until it &#8220;un-stuck&#8221; and then putting it all back together.  I don&#8217;t think I&#8217;d try this unless you have no other option (exchange it where you bought it, call Hasbro support and see if they will send you a new one etc).  If nothing else pans out, its the only option I&#8217;m finding online.   If you&#8217;re desperate, Watch <a href="http://youtu.be/fNaNM4_fKTo" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">THIS VIDEO </a>to see how it was done on the old Furby.</p>

				</div>
			
			</div>
			
		</div>

