	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-179">
	
		<div class="the-comment">
		
			<img alt='Eric' src='http://www.furbymanual.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/furby_510x317-60x60.jpg' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' />
			
			<div class="comment-arrow"></div>
			
			<div class="comment-box">
			
				<div class="comment-author">
					<strong>admin</strong>
					<small>February 24, 2013 at 6:05 pm</a> - <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/troubleshooting-your-furby/?replytocom=179#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("-179", "179", "respond", "167")'>Reply</a></small>
				</div>
			
				<div class="comment-text">
					
					<p>If you&#8217;ve followed all the steps in &#8220;Troubleshooting your Furby&#8221; and it is still not working, you must have a mechanical problem and will either need to return it where you bought it, or call Hasbro customer service and see what they can do for you.   I wish there was an easy fix for &#8220;frozen&#8221; eyes, mouth and ears that I could share with you.  Weak batteries can cause this problem, but if you&#8217;ve replaced them, It must be mechanical issue.</p>

				</div>
			
			</div>
			
		</div>

